	"body" : "<p>✒ <a href=\"http://www.sajidjavid.com/\" title=\"\">Sajid Javid</a>, David Cameron's emergency replacement for Maria Miller, is manifestly the least-qualified of the coalition government's culture secretaries. Jeremy Hunt had a degree of credibility due to his background in PR and publishing, while Maria Miller had a career in advertising and marketing before becoming an MP. In contrast, Javid's CV, stuffed with impressive banking jobs, includes no relevant experience whatsoever.</p><p>✒ This glaring gap posed no problem for the writers of last week's laudatory and sometimes adulatory profiles in rightwing papers, which Javid, eagerly provided links to on his website: perhaps too eagerly for rival post-Cameron contenders, even including his mentor George Osborne, given their headlines included such phrases as \"tipped as future leader\", \"Maggie's Muslim heir\" and \"could end up at top of Tory tree\". And Javid's lack of cultural hinterland – his Who's Who entry lists no recreations – was acknowledged but relegated to the 14th paragraph of <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/10757640/Sajid-Javid-the-man-who-thinks-big.html\" title=\"\">Fraser Nelson's Telegraph profile</a> (\"he will stuggle to talk about his great love of the performing arts … It is certainly an odd casting – Javid's expertise is in finance\") and the 23rd of <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2601111/The-Muslim-bus-drivers-son-set-Commons-superstar-ANDREW-PIERCE-new-Culture-Secretary-Sajid-Javid.html\" title=\"\">Andrew Pierce's huzzah in the Mail</a>: \"His knowledge of sport may be scant – he claims to support Manchester United – and few of his friends have heard him talking about culture and the arts.\" All irrelevant, apparently.</p><p>✒ Each piece touching on Javid's nonexistent credentials will have added to the grief of the Hon <a href=\"http://www.vaizey.com/\" title=\"\">Ed Vaizey</a>, who – since he's been at the DCMS since the coalition came to power, as well as being a leading art critic's son – has the expertise his new boss lacks. Overlooked again, he might well be wondering who's more insulting to lose out to – Maria Miller, or a media and culture know-nothing? Clearly one of the amiable under-minister's handicaps on this occasion was the difficulty of handing over one of Miller's other jobs to him (in contrast to Javid, who has taken her equalities role), as neither being a toff nor being chubby  – \"I am an obese man!\" he once told a stunned audience – currently qualifies for discriminated-against minority status. He may need to develop lifestyle choices that put him in a better position next time, such as turning his hair ginger or becoming a goth. Omitting mention of his public school, as he does on his website's \"About Ed\" section, is a sensible start to this brand-building. Oxford must go next.</p><p>✒ In a splendid week for hairless men, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/apr/06/telegraph-jason-seiken-digital-saviour-familiar-route\" title=\"\">Telegraph editor-in-chief Jason Seiken</a> shared his ideas on the need for newsrooms to be dominated by \"digital natives\" in a visionary address at the Newsworks conference. Telegraph toilers too mature or luddite to qualify (digital incomers? Digital foreigners?) will have been alarmed by his blunt implicit message for them, but compelling too was his sketch of a topsy-turvy ethos modelled on \"his last job at PBS\" where he \"created a 'failure goal' that penalised staff who did not fail enough\". As he explained: \"It meant they weren't challenging themselves enough, they were playing it safe. At the Telegraph that's the digital native culture we embrace.\" Monkey (and doubtless the paper's star writers such as Peter Oborne, Boris Johnson, Allison Pearson and Matthew Norman) can't wait for the first failure league tables to be leaked.</p><p>✒ Meanwhile, two former Telegraph editors were once again entertainingly at loggerheads, this time over Maria Miller. With his stint as <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/mediamonkeyblog/2014/feb/25/telegraph-editor-waiting-tony-gallagher\" title=\"\">work-experience chef in a London restaurant over, Tony Gallagher</a> had plenty of <a href=\"https://twitter.com/gallaghereditor\" title=\"\">time to tweet about the minister's downfall being long overdue</a>, having driven the paper's campaign against her before <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/jan/21/tony-gallagher-exits-daily-telegraph-editor\" title=\"\">he was sacked after Seiken's arrival</a>. Over in the <a href=\"http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/charles-moore/2014/04/maria-miller-should-not-have-resigned/\" title=\"\">Spectator, in contrast, Charles Moore</a> (once described by Gallagher in an email to a colleague as a \"tw*t\") called Miller's resignation \"a disgrace\" and denounced \"the press anger\" that he believed forced her to go as \"confected\". It's a feud promisingly turning into Torydum v Torydee.</p><p>✒ Also in the Spectator, Daily Mail columnist Jan Moir revealed that her octogenarian mother, who reads the paper on her iPad, seems to treat Moir's rants much like many of her critics: \"She now bypasses my articles completely and goes straight to the reader comments, which she adores. The more brutal and rude they are about me, the deeper her enjoyment.\"</p><p>✒ Coverage of last week's <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/apr/07/bafta-tv-award-nominations-full-list\" title=\"\">Bafta TV nominations</a>, being naturally drawn to stars, dramas and reality shows, tended to overlook how awful for the BBC the journalism categories were, just as in the recent RTS journalism awards. In current affairs, the empire James Harding inherited was shut out completely, with all four nominations going to Channel 4 (which also easily won the overall battle, with 27 noms compared to 17 apiece for BBC1 and BBC2 and 12 for ITV); and in news coverage the mighty network news machine (aka \"snoozegathering\") again no-scored, although a BBC Northwest Tonight special did get the nod alongside two ITV reports and one from Channel 4. For a BBC now run by its former emperor of news, this is pretty shaming.</p><p>✒ Kim Shillinglaw, new controller of BBC2 and BBC4, inherits a rich legacy from her predecessor Janice Hadlow, including the substantial <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2014/eighteenth-century-britain.html\" title=\"\">18th-century season</a> that is already unfolding on the two channels and looks likely to climax in early May when \"history pixie\" Lucy Worsley completes her three-parter, The First Georgians. In a curious coincidence, the first week of May was the date originally announced for Hadlow's long-awaited first book, about the private life of George III (worryingly, her publishers seem unsure what they're calling it, The Strangest Family or A Royal Experiment); now its publication has been moved to summer, the season won't be quite so close in timing but is still bound to leave viewers eager to learn more about those beguiling Georgians.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/434343810|2014-05-04T10:23:41Z|77b2ba0f7294abddc11c45d9d6d51db572e65e71 -->",
