	"body" : "<div id=\"block-53440ea8e4b053db358db0e5\" class=\"block is-summary\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T16:11:07.542+01:00\">4.11pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Afternoon summary</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><b>• Mary Macleod, Maria Miller's parliamentary private secretary, has accused the media of attacking Miller because they are angry about her support for gay marriage and the Leveson-backed royal charter on press regulation. </b></p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/rosschawkins/statuses/453541968514383872\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>MacLeod on camera: think this is a witch hunt by the media angry about Leveson &amp; equal marriage &amp; taking it out on Maria</p>— Ross Hawkins (@rosschawkins) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/rosschawkins/statuses/453541968514383872\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/rosschawkins/statuses/453545371407777792\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>MacLeod: : &quot;We can't just let the media do whatever they want and hound someone where allegations have been dismissed&quot;</p>— Ross Hawkins (@rosschawkins) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/rosschawkins/statuses/453545371407777792\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>Number 10 has not endorsed this claim.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/paulwaugh/statuses/453548575809875969\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>No.10 stonewalling re Miller. Asked if Mary Macleod speaks for Govt, refuses to comment directly.</p>— Paul Waugh (@paulwaugh) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/paulwaugh/statuses/453548575809875969\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> <p><b>• Ireland's president, Michael D Higgins, has met the Queen on the first ever state visit to the UK by the country's head of state.</b></p><p><b>• The chairman of the Police Federation, who yesterday announced his intention to quit, has complained about being &quot;gratuitously and cruelly bullied and humiliated&quot; by the organisation's top brass when he tried to push through reforms.</b> As the Press Association reports, a message from <b>Steve Williams </b>to members of the Federation's Joint Central Committee, published by MPs today, pleaded for their support and said the bile aimed at him was &quot;a straw that edged on breaking the camel's back&quot;. The letter was published today after the group's former director of communications Fiona McElroy, who was sacked by another federation boss, gave evidence to the Home Affairs Select Committee last week. It said:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>I know some of you have described what has happened as 'venting the spleen' exercises or 'a little bit of bloodletting' but it is simply wrong and is not how we should treat colleagues or indeed as I like to think of many of you, a friend. </p><p>We are all rightly entitled to our opinion but as professional police officers and federation officials, it is how we express those opinions that matter. Whilst accepting emotions are running high in the advent of inevitable change, at times I have genuinely felt that I have been gratuitously and cruelly bullied and humiliated.</p></blockquote><p>That's all from me for today.</p><p>We've got PMQs tomorrow. It should be good ...</p><p>Thanks for the comments.</p><blockquote></blockquote> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T16:58:08.887+01:00\">at 4.58pm BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-53440d8be4b06c7e09a60232\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T15:57:37.161+01:00\">3.57pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><a href=\"http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/coffeehouse/2014/04/more-tory-mps-break-cover-on-miller/?utm_source=rss&amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;utm_campaign=more-tory-mps-break-cover-on-miller&amp;utm_source=twitterfeed&amp;utm_medium=twitter\">Isabel Hardman at Coffee House has a good audioBoo selection of Tory MPs ( Mark Field, Zac Goldsmith and Matthew Offord) having a go at Maria Miller.</a></p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-53440c5ce4b053db358db0e2\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T15:50:01.750+01:00\">3.50pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The Telegraph's Holly Watt has hit back at Maria Miller's PPS, Mary Macleod. (See <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/2014/apr/08/maria-millers-expenses-controversy-latest-developments-politics-live-blog#block-5344062fe4b06c7e09a60227\">3.25pm.)</a></p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/holly_watt/statuses/453544793034207232\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>It is offensive to suggest Miller story is in any way about equal marriage &amp; only person who mentioned Leveson was DCMS spad</p>— holly watt (@holly_watt) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/holly_watt/statuses/453544793034207232\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T16:16:07.802+01:00\">at 4.16pm BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-53440aaee4b06c7e09a60230\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T15:43:25.206+01:00\">3.43pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>During the urgent question<b> Sir Kevin Barron</b>, the chair of the Commons standards committee, said the committee met this morning and authorised him to issue a statement defending their report into Maria Miller.</p><p>Here it is.</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>At our meeting today the committee authorised me to say that it continues to believe that its individual adjudications are impartial, non partisan and fair. It is extremely important that those who express opinions on these cases both within this House and outside it should have read closely the carefully reasoned and evidence based conclusions set out in each report. The committee will continue to work closely and cooperatively with the commissioner to reach objective non partisan and fair adjudications.</p></blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-53440935e4b06c7e09a6022b\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T15:39:46.553+01:00\">3.39pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Here's the Sun's &quot;Miller must quit&quot; banner. (See<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/2014/apr/08/maria-millers-expenses-controversy-latest-developments-politics-live-blog#block-5343c325e4b06c7e09a60197\"> 10.40am.)</a></p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/Sun_Politics/statuses/453541244396785665\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>In the words of her special advisor Jo Hindley, <a href=\"https://twitter.com/TheSunNewspaper\">@TheSunNewspaper</a>'s message to Maria Miller today; <a href=\"http://t.co/czG9qEI97F\">pic.twitter.com/czG9qEI97F</a></p>— Sun Politics (@Sun_Politics) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/Sun_Politics/statuses/453541244396785665\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>&quot;Just thought we'd flag that up&quot; is a reference to <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/apr/04/maria-miller-telegraph-releases-taped-call\">what Miller's adviser, Jo Hindley, told the Telegraph when she was apparently trying to warn them off investigating her boss. </a></p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5344062fe4b06c7e09a60227\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T15:25:21.968+01:00\">3.25pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The Conservative MP <b>Mary Macleod</b> has been tweeting support for Mary Miller.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/MaryMacleodMP/statuses/453475131961405440\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Full support for <a href=\"https://twitter.com/Maria_MillerMP\">@maria_millermp</a> as she has been cleared of allegations but still hounded by media. She is an excellent Culture Secretary.</p>— Mary Macleod (@MaryMacleodMP) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/MaryMacleodMP/statuses/453475131961405440\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>That's not especially surprising; Macleod is Miller's parliamentary private secretary.</p><p><a href=\"http://order-order.com/2014/04/08/exclusive-troubled-miller-hits-back-claiming-levesen-smears/\">According to Guido Fawkes,</a> Macleod has also been texting Tory MPs telling them Miller is the victim of a media witch hunt and asking them to support the culture secretary.</p> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-6dc910c2-c8ae-40f8-a1e5-e00bf7213e99\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/4/8/1396971300526/90aa8178-8d42-40ff-8e9e-6c6ecbb552ff-bestSizeAvailable.jpeg\" alt=\"Screen grab of text message posted on Guido Fawkes' blog\" width=\"420\" height=\"252\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Screen grab of text message posted on Guido Fawkes' blog Guido Fawkes blog</figcaption> </figure> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T16:35:05.680+01:00\">at 4.35pm BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-5343f69be4b06c7e09a6020a\" class=\"block is-summary\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T14:58:27.848+01:00\">2.58pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Lunchtime summary</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><b>• Maria Miller, the embattled culture secretary, has come under fresh pressure from her Conservative colleagues to resign. Mark Field</b>, the MP for Cities of London and Westminster, told the World at One that her apology last week was &quot;unacceptably perfunctory&quot;. He said MPs who entered the Commons in 2010 felt particularly strongly about this.</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>They of course felt when they were elected four years ago that they were untainted by the expenses scandal of 2009, yet they of course have now also felt the real backlash from their constituents over recent days ...</p><p>There is this whole public perception here that, rightly or wrongly, the standards committee as it is currently constituted is somehow open to being nobbled by senior government members. In many ways it is that public perception that is so damaging here. </p></blockquote><p><b>Philip Davies</b>, the MP for Shipley, said on the Daily Politics that the affair was &quot;extremely damaging&quot; for the Conservatives. </p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Whether [Miller] resigns is a matter for her but obviously the whole thing is extremely damaging for the Conservative party, it's damaging for parliament as a whole and politicians - we all get tarnished by the same brush. It's damaging for the government, for the prime minister. The sooner the matter is resolved, the better.</p></blockquote><p>And<b> Jacob Rees-Mogg</b>, the North East Somerset MP, told MPs that the Commons as a whole could, if it chose, decided to ignore the standards committee and make its own recommendations &quot;which may be more robust&quot;.<br /><b><br /></b></p><p><b>• The three lay members of the Commons standards committee - members of the public who are entitled to take part in its proceedings, but not vote, under reforms brought in after 2010 - have called for a &quot;fundamental rewrite&quot; of the rules governing MPs.</b> In a report at once measured and rather damning, they virtually accused the Commons of hypocrisy, saying it imposed standards on other bodies that it did not follow itself. (See <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/2014/apr/08/maria-millers-expenses-controversy-latest-developments-politics-live-blog#block-5343eb77e4b053db358db0c2\">2.03pm.)</a><b> Sir Kevin Barron,</b> chair of the committee, said that the committee was already committed to reviewing the current system and that it would consider the lay members' recommendations.<br /></p><p><b>• Andrew Lansley, the leader of the Commons, has said that introducing self-regulation for MPs would undermine the independence of the Commons. </b>Responding to an urgent question in the Commons, he said that the system had already been reformed, and that the Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority (Ipsa), which is independent, was now in charge of investigating complaints about expenses. But he expressed reservations about going further.</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>For a wholly external body to consider complaints relating to the conduct of members in this House - for example on participation in debates and the registration of financial interests - risks undermining parliamentary privilege.</p></blockquote><p>Lansley said, if the parliamentary commissioner for standards were wholly independent, she would find it harder to investigate MPs. </p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>If we were to seek, for example, to make the standards committee or the commissioner wholly independent, the position we would end up with would be the commissioner for standards would no longer have access to parliamentary privilege in relation to her investigations. </p><p>Presently she does, by virtue of her investigation being part of the proceeding of the standards committee of this House. Her role would be much more difficult to fulfil in the way she does. </p></blockquote><p>Lansley said the government was open to the idea of strengthening the &quot;independent input&quot; of the lay members of the standards committee. Number 10 has suggested they could be given a vote. But Lansley said the lay members can already issue a dissenting view to a report, and that this was more powerful than having a vote.</p><p><b>• Lansley signalled that legislation to allow the &quot;recall&quot; of MPs will be introduced in the Queen's Speech.</b></p><p><b>• Sir Gerald Howarth, a Conservative MP, has accused the media of engaging in a witch hunt against Maria Miller. </b>This is what he said during the urgent question.</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>This is is not so much a failure of the system but a complete and abject failure of the media properly to report these matters objectively, the result of which is many of our constituents have failed completely to understand exactly what has been the case in a recent report and it is time the media should pay proper consideration to Parliamentary reports rather than seeking to engage in witch hunts.</p></blockquote><p>Other MPs defended the current arrangements and urged people to read the standards committee's report into Miller in full. <b>Sir Nick Harvey</b>, a Lib Dem member of the committee, said he thought the system was working well.</p><p><b>• Sir Anthony May, the interception of communications commissioner, has said that fears of a &quot;significant institutional overuse&quot; by police forces of powers to access communications data are to be investigated. </b>Police officers and members of law enforcement agencies, such as the National Crime Agency, may be neglecting their duty to consider the impact their actions have on an individual's privacy, May said in a report.. As the Press Association reports, May has decided to launch an inquiry into potential overuse after 514,608 requests for communications data were approved in 2013, which, despite being a 9% drop on the previous year, struck the commissioner as being a &quot;very large number&quot;. &quot;It's an inquiry which starts from this raw figure - 514,608,&quot; Sir Anthony said. &quot;The bulk of that figure is from criminal investigations in this jurisdiction and I have reckoned that's a large number and needs looking into, so I instructed the inspectors to do so.&quot; </p><p><b><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/2014/apr/08/maria-millers-expenses-controversy-latest-developments-politics-live-blog#block-5343d01be4b053db358db078\">• Ed Miliband has set out details of his plans to devolve power to &quot;city-regions&quot;. </a></b></p><p><b><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/apr/08/uk-economy-growth-outperform-imf\">• The IMF says Britain will be the best performing of the world's major economies this year with growth of 2.9%.</a></b><br /></p><p><b>• Andrew Lansley has announced the Queen's Speech has been put back due to a planned G7 summit in Brussels. </b>It will now take place on Wednesday June 4 - a day later than planned. </p><p><b><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/apr/08/scottish-independence-lord-robertson-uk-global-status\">• Lord Robertson, the former defence secretary and Nato chief, has claimed that Scottish independence would have a &quot;cataclysmic&quot; effect on European and global stability by undermining the UK on the world stage.</a></b></p><p><b>• Alex Salmond, Scotland's first minister, has used a speech in New York to say an independent Scotland would use &quot;enlightened self-interest&quot; to become a force for good in the world.</b></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>You can aspire to be a great nation, without desiring to be a great power. The USA is both but most nations can't be, and they reduce their chance to be a great nation if they pretend to be a great power</p><p>For most countries, greatness can only come from influence, not force; from soft, not hard power; from enlightened self-interest, not self-interest alone. </p><p>It will come from their people, their values, their reputation and their ideas and it starts with good governance at home.</p></blockquote> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T15:06:38.292+01:00\">at 3.06pm BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-5343eb77e4b053db358db0c2\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T14:03:29.919+01:00\">2.03pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Report on Commons self-regulation by the 3 lay members of standards committee - Summary</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The report from the three lay members of the Commons standards committee - Sharon Darcy, Peter Jinman and Walter Rader - <a href=\"http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-committees/Standards%20Committee/Lay%20Members%20Report.pdf\">only runs to 12 pages (pdf).</a> It is written in cautious, neutral language, and it is (generally) devoid of any juicy revelations.</p><p>But it is also, in a quiet, understated way, rather devastating.</p><p>Plenty of people have criticised the Commons' system of self-regulation for MPs. But this is a critique from three Establishment individuals, appointed because they were deemed fair-minded and committed to high standards in public life (and, presumably, not hostile to parliament), who for the last 12 months have had a much better &quot;inside view&quot; into the way the Commons standards committee works than any outsiders in the past.</p><p>And they have concluded that the system is flawed.</p><p>Here are the main points they make.</p><p><b>• They call for a &quot;fundamental rewrite&quot; of the rules governing the conduct of MPs.</b></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>A fundamental rewrite of The Code of Conduct and The Guide to the Rules, with close attention given to the way in which these are presented and communicated, would, in our opinion, help ensure that these important documents are both seen to be fit for purpose and future proofed for the digital world and for the next Parliament. </p></blockquote><p><b>• They reveal that some MPs claim to be &quot;too busy&quot; for standards.</b></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Several of those we have met have said that Elected Members were often ‘too busy to spend much time on standards.’</p></blockquote><p><b>• The lay members suggest that MPs have just paid &quot;lip service&quot; to standards in the past.</b></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>If the House is to show that it is not just paying lip service to the importance of high standards then, in our view, more needs to be done to ensure that leadership (one of the seven principles of public life), is shown in this area. We observe that the extent to which the Committee on Standards should lead in this area, and be at the forefront of championing wider cultural change, would be worth exploring. </p></blockquote><p><b>• They say the Commons should produce a clear statement about what the role of an MP is. </b></p><p><b>• They say the absence of such a statement has allowed some MPs to say they don't know how they should behave.</b></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Once the high level ‘core purpose’ of an Elected Member’s role has been described / clarified, setting and assessing the standards of conduct which Members should meet can become more focused.</p><p>Over the last twelve months, the Lay Members have observed that the fragmentation of the current standards system has enabled some to say that the conduct which is expected from them is unclear. The opaqueness of the letter of the law has the potential to enable those so minded to ignore the spirit of the law, as encapsulated in the seven principles of public life. In our view, even once the Guide to the Rules is tightened up, this will remain a risk unless it is made clear that behavior will always be interpreted within the context of the spirit of the law.</p></blockquote><p><b>• The lay members virtually accuse the Commons of hypocrisy - saying it imposes standards on other bodies that it does not always follow itself.</b></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>From the public point of view, Elected Members set the rules / laws that the rest of the population live by. The Lay Members note that some of the rules that have been set for both public facing organisations and private corporations (e.g. expectations of behavior, commitment to openness and transparency or staff disciplinary procedures) do not appear to be fully followed by the House itself.</p></blockquote><p><b>• They suggest that a system of double standards has been allowed to apply in the past.</b><br /></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>When Elected Members decide that different standards of behaviour are acceptable from them, as compared to other external public figures, we are of the view that a clear evidence base should always be used, and communicated, to publicly explain the reasons for this decision. </p></blockquote><p><b>• They reveal that MPs on the standards committee sometimes miss meetings because they have other engagements.</b> Once this meant the lay members were paid to attend a meeting that had to be cancelled.</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Over the last year we have observed the heavy and demanding workloads required of Elected Members [of the standards committee]. Many will frequently be scheduled to be in one or more meetings at the same time that the Standards Committee is meeting, as well as having to prepare for debates and deal with mounting constituency business. On one occasion this led to a situation where only the Lay Members were present with the Chair and the Clerk at a Committee meeting, although we were assured that this had not happened previously. This rendered the Committee non-quorate and must be considered unacceptable given the cost to the public purse.</p></blockquote><p><b>• The lay members say it is not entirely clear who is in charge of the self-regulation process.</b></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>It is also currently unclear who is in the ‘strategic driving seat’ in the Committee. Is it the Committee Chair, the Committee as a whole, the Commissioner or indeed even the Lay Members?</p></blockquote><p>The three lay members of the Commons standards committee are: Sharon Darcy, a trustee at the National Employment Savings Trust; Peter Jinman, a former president of Royal College of Veterinary Surgeons; and Walter Rader, a former chief executive of the Big Lottery Fund in Northern Ireland.</p><p><b> <br /></b></p><p><b> <br /></b></p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e8dae4b053db358db0ba\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T13:19:44.199+01:00\">1.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Here is<a href=\"http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-committees/Standards%20Committee/Lay%20Members%20Report.pdf\"> the report from lay members of the Commons standards committee (pdf) </a>mentioned earlier. (See <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/2014/apr/08/maria-millers-expenses-controversy-latest-developments-politics-live-blog#block-5343e1cde4b06c7e09a601dd\">12.49pm</a> and<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/2014/apr/08/maria-millers-expenses-controversy-latest-developments-politics-live-blog#block-5343e74ae4b053db358db0b1\"> 1.11pm.)</a></p><p>I will post a summary of it soon.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e7cbe4b06c7e09a601f2\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T13:14:18.213+01:00\">1.14pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Labour's<b> Thomas Docherty </b>asks why David Cameron wants to end self-regulation for the press, but not for MPs.</p><p>Lansley says having lay members on the standards committee was intended to introduce a system akin to a body like the Bar Council. But there are issues of privilege to be taken into account, he says.</p><p>The UQ is over. I will post a summary shortly.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T13:15:16.955+01:00\">at 1.15pm BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e791e4b053db358db0b3\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T13:12:56.517+01:00\">1.12pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><b>Bob Blackman</b>, a Conservative, asks how many &quot;legacy cases&quot; there are (ie, unresolved expenses complaints relating to before 2010.)</p><p>Lansley says he does not know the number. He hopes there are relatively few. But he cannot say there are none.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e74ae4b053db358db0b1\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T13:11:30.594+01:00\">1.11pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>My colleague Patrick Wintour has been looking at what the lay members of the standards committee have been saying in the report Sir Kevin Barron mentioned earlier.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/patrickwintour/statuses/453504727133978624\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Lay members of standards committee have risen up - want new code of conduct, and tell MPs to stop paying lip service to higher standards.</p>— Patrick Wintour (@patrickwintour) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/patrickwintour/statuses/453504727133978624\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>I will post more on this later.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e6f0e4b053db358db0b0\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T13:10:29.128+01:00\">1.10pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><b>Matthew Offord</b>, a Conservative, says people did raise expenses with him when he knocked on doors at the weekend. He says people think the situation has not changed.</p><p>Lansley says MPs should tell people that the situation has changed.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e6a7e4b053db358db0ae\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T13:09:08.718+01:00\">1.09pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Labour's <b>Sheila Gilmore</b> asks if Lansley is really unwilling to consider reform proposals.</p><p>Lansley says that is not his position. He would consider changes.</p><p>But he wants MPs to understand how much the situation has already changed.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e63ee4b06c7e09a601ed\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T13:08:04.125+01:00\">1.08pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><b>Peter Bone</b>, a Conservative, says he has been doorstepping and telephone canvassing in recent days. Only one issue came up - immigration. The Miller case was only mentioned once, he says.</p><p>He says they should have recall - and &quot;pure recall&quot; (ie, a system that does not rely on the standards committee approving a recall ballot).</p><p>Lansley says Bone will have to wait for the government's plans to be published.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e576e4b06c7e09a601eb\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T13:06:18.304+01:00\">1.06pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Labour's<b> Chris Bryant</b> says there is no point complaining about the media on this issue. The system of self-regulation for MPs has been on trial for some time. And it has been found wanting, he says.</p><p>There is &quot;as much dodginess&quot; in the Lords as there is in the Commons too, he says.</p><p>Lansley says he was not trying to blame the media. But MPs need to be honest with themselves, he says. They are still in transition from an old system to a new one. The sooner legacy cases can be resolved, the better, he says.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e532e4b06c7e09a601e8\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T13:02:56.409+01:00\">1.02pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Labour's <b>Paul Flynn </b>says the expenses system should be replaced with a system of allowances. Isn't Ipsa an idea whose time has gone?</p><p>Lansley says none of the recent cases imply Ipsa has been at fault, because they do not relate to cases since 2010.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e504e4b06c7e09a601e6\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T13:01:48.960+01:00\">1.01pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Lansley says there was a concern that giving lay members voting rights on a committee could led to that committee losing its parliamentary privilege in the eyes of a court.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e4a9e4b053db358db0aa\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T13:00:52.975+01:00\">1.00pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><b>Therese Coffey</b>, a Conservative, says a green paper on parliamentary privilege two years ago led to the introduction of lay members.</p><p>She says it was the standards committee that decided to reopen an investigation into a former member (Denis MacShane) that led to him being jailed. So it is independent, she says.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e43ee4b053db358db0a8\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T12:59:31.706+01:00\">12.59pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Labour's <b>Ben Bradshaw</b> says he thought self-regulation had gone. What can Lansley say to assure people that reform has not stopped.</p><p>Lansley says the public are concerned about expenses. There are some &quot;legacy cases&quot; relating to the past. But the rules have changed, and Ipsa have created a situation that should command public respect.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e419e4b06c7e09a601e5\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T12:57:38.192+01:00\">12.57pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Back in the chamber, Lansley says he does not see how it would be acceptable to allow an external body to take a decision to expel an MP from the House.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e3ebe4b053db358db0a7\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T12:57:05.496+01:00\">12.57pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Outside the chamber another Conservative MP has admitted that the Miller affair is damaging the party.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/politicshome/statuses/453499633080475648\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Tory MP .<a href=\"https://twitter.com/PhilipDaviesMP\">@PhilipDaviesMP</a> on Maria Miller expenses: &quot;Obviously the whole thing is extremely damaging for the Conservative party&quot; <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23bbcdp&amp;src=hash\">#bbcdp</a></p>— PoliticsHome (@politicshome) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/politicshome/statuses/453499633080475648\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e3abe4b053db358db0a6\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T12:56:24.722+01:00\">12.56pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Labour's <b>David Winnick</b> says he does not accept the idea that this was all &quot;got up&quot; by the media. Mistakes have been made, he says. The system has to satisfy the public. At the moment they think there are double standards, he says.</p><p>Lansley says he is not being complacent. </p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e343e4b053db358db0a5\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T12:55:03.598+01:00\">12.55pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><b>Jacob Rees-Mogg</b>, a Conservative, says he wants parliament to retain control over regulation of MPs. But there should either be a proper power of recall, he says, or disciplinary decisions should be taken by the Commons as a whole.</p><p>Lansley says the government is committed to recall legislation.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e2cde4b06c7e09a601e0\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T12:53:34.698+01:00\">12.53pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Labour's<b> Peter Hain,</b> a former leader of the Commons, says the public think there is one rule of them, and one rule for MPs. </p><p>Lansley says if the parliamentary commissioner for standards were independent, she would not be covered by parliamentary privilege. Her investigations would be subject to legal challenge, he says. </p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e267e4b06c7e09a601df\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T12:51:38.839+01:00\">12.51pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><b>Sir Peter Bottomley,</b> a Conservative, says he resigned from the standards committee when the House authorities, and at least one party, trashed Elizabeth Filkin, a previous parliamentary commissioner for standards. He is referring to Labour.</p><p>The media should read the committee's reports, he says.</p><p>Lansley says he encourages members, and the press, to read the whole of the Miller report. That is the only way to gain a balanced view, he says.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e1cde4b06c7e09a601dd\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T12:49:32.539+01:00\">12.49pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><b>Sir Kevin Barron</b>, chair of the committee, says the lay members of the committee recently submitted a report on their reflections on their first year on the committee.</p><p>That paper is on the committee's website, he says.</p><p>He says the committee is considering the way it operates.</p><p>The committee continues to believe is decisions are fair, impartial and non-partisan, he says.</p><p>It will continue to do this, he says.</p><p>Lansley says the Commons looks to the standards committee to advise it on how regulation can be as robust as possible.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e16ae4b06c7e09a601dc\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T12:47:20.021+01:00\">12.47pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><b>Sir Nick Harvey,</b> a Lib Dem MP, says he is on the standards committee. Until recently he did not realise they did not have a vote. That's because they don't need one. They contribute greatly to its discussions, he says. They have brought a great deal of expertise to the system. It should carry on as it is.</p><p>Lansley says that, if the lay members were to dissent from a committee report, that would have a powerful effect.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e144e4b053db358db09d\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T12:45:42.203+01:00\">12.45pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><b>John Bercow</b>, the Commons Speaker, says MPs should not be debating Miller. MPs can only debate the conduct of an MP if there is a substantive motion, he says.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e06de4b06c7e09a601da\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T12:45:04.463+01:00\">12.45pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><b>Angela Eagle,</b> the shadow leader of the Commons, says this affair has cast doubt on the conduct of Miller, and the judgment of the prime minister.</p><p>Will the government remove the government majority on the standards committee? And will it give lay members voting rights?</p><p>Lansley says Eagle should not have criticised Miller personally. He thought that was not allowed during these exchanges.</p><p>He says he read the standards committee and agreed with its approach. He does not think partisan considerations affect its decisions, he says.</p><p>He says if the lay members had expressed a dissenting view, as they are allowed to, that would have been more powerful than casting a vote. So effectively they have a casting vote, he says. Their power is greater than it would be if they just had a vote.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343e038e4b06c7e09a601d8\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T12:41:30.780+01:00\">12.41pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><b>Sir Gerald Howarth</b>, a Conservative, backs Lansley.</p><p>He accuses the media of misrepresenting the standards committee's report.</p><p>Lansley says, if constituents do not understand the system, MPs should explain it.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343dfdde4b06c7e09a601d5\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T12:40:37.505+01:00\">12.40pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Lansley is replying to Mann.</p><p>He says Ipsa is &quot;wholly independent&quot; of the Commons.</p><p>Making the parliamentary commissioner for standards wholly independent would mean that her investigation would no longer be protected by parliamentary privilege, he says. At the moment it is, because it is part of a parliamentary process.</p><p>He says the standards committee's thinking is transparent.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343df9be4b053db358db09b\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T12:39:07.057+01:00\">12.39pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><b>John Mann </b>says Lansley has probably not spent much time on doorsteps recently.</p><p>If he had, he would know how unhappy the public are.</p><p>Why won't he back independent regulation?</p><p>And, if he won't back that, will be ensure that all the committee's proceedings are made public?</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343ded3e4b053db358db099\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T12:37:59.713+01:00\">12.37pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><b>Andrew Lansley</b> describes the role of the standards committee and Ipsa.</p><p>As of now, Ipsa is wholly independent, he says, and it considers expenses complaints. It can demand repayment and impose a fine.</p><p>But it is not in charge of complaints relating to the period before 2010, he says.</p><p>He says there are now three lay members on the standards committee. By convention, the committee chair seeks consensus.</p><p>The regulation of MPs is a matter for the Commons.</p><p>Having an external body adjudicate on these matters would undermine the independence of the Commons, he says.</p><p>Having lay members on the committee should increase public confidence in the system, he says.</p><p>He says the Commons can also make its processes more transparent.</p><p>The government would be open to giving lay members more say, he says, provided that does not undermine the independence of the Commons.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343deb4e4b06c7e09a601d3\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T12:34:39.393+01:00\">12.34pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><b>John Mann </b>asks for a statement on the possible changes suggested by David Cameron yesterday to the Commons disciplinary committees.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343de45e4b053db358db098\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T12:33:02.123+01:00\">12.33pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Here's the latest from Number 10 on Maria Miller.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/JBeattieMirror/statuses/453494203327463424\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Asked if Maria Miller has offered resignation, No 10 says &quot;matter has not arisen&quot;. You could fall into the space left open there</p>— Jason Beattie (@JBeattieMirror) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/JBeattieMirror/statuses/453494203327463424\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343dd8de4b06c7e09a601d0\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T12:31:18.681+01:00\">12.31pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Andrew Lansley's statement on Commons standards</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><b>Andrew Lansley</b>, the leader of the Commons, is about to answer an urgent question on Commons standards. </p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/HouseofCommons/statuses/453473763661991936\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>One Urgent Question today from <a href=\"https://twitter.com/JohnMannMP\">@JohnMannMP</a> on regulating complaints about fellow <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23MPs&amp;src=hash\">#MPs</a>. More details to follow.</p>— House of Commons (@HouseofCommons) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/HouseofCommons/statuses/453473763661991936\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>My colleague Patrick Wintour points out that Lansley recently said he was opposed to giving lay members of the Commons standards committee a vote when it produces its reports.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/patrickwintour/statuses/453482170385178624\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Andrew Lansley leader of house 3 months ago rejected plans to pass legislation to give decisions of committees with lay members privilege.</p>— Patrick Wintour (@patrickwintour) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/patrickwintour/statuses/453482170385178624\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343dbd7e4b06c7e09a601c7\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T12:23:45.814+01:00\">12.23pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>That expression of support didn't last long. (See<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/2014/apr/08/maria-millers-expenses-controversy-latest-developments-politics-live-blog#block-5343a4f4e4b06c7e09a60155\"> 8.41am.)</a> Boris Johnson is now cracking jokes at the expense of Maria Miller.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/sammacrory/statuses/453481051219066880\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>'If things were to go wrong for Maria there's plenty of jobs in life sciences' - Boris' Miller solution at the MedCity launch</p>— Sam Macrory (@sammacrory) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/sammacrory/statuses/453481051219066880\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343d01be4b053db358db078\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T12:15:41.445+01:00\">12.15pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Ed Miliband's speech on the cost of living crisis - Summary</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>This morning<b> Ed Miliband </b>has delivered a speech on the cost of living crisis. On a normal day it would probably get some coverage on 24 hours news, but the BBC and Sky are obsessed with Oscar Pistorius giving evidence in his trial. </p><p><a href=\"http://press.labour.org.uk/post/82080311502/ed-milibands-speech-on-tackling-the-cost-of-living\">The full text of Miliband's speech is now available.</a> And here is Patrick Wintour's preview story summarising the key announcement.</p><p>The speech itself does not add anything radically new to what was released in advance. But it fleshes it out. And it's an important speech, because it proposes a significant transfer of power away from Whitehall (or what looks like a beefed-up version of the city deal programme already pioneered by the government).<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/education/2014/feb/09/ed-miliband-labour-parents-headteachers\"> In his Hugo Young lecture in February Miliband presented himself as a genuine decentraliser; </a>today's speech suggests that he really meant it.</p><p>Here are the key points.</p><p><b>• Ed Miliband said the government had to do much more to promote growth outside London. </b>The coalition is also committed to this goal, but Miliband said that its policies were not working.</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>The country that once built its prosperity on the great towns and cities, like Birmingham, Bristol, Liverpool, Leeds, Manchester, Glasgow and Cardiff, has become a country which doesn’t do enough to build prosperity in England outside one great capital city: London ...</p><p>London and the South-East of England was responsible for 37 per cent of the UK's growth in the decade before the financial crisis.</p><p> And in the years since 2010 that share has risen to 54 per cent.</p><p>More than half the growth of the whole of our country taking place in London and the south-east ...</p><p>Britain will never be able to tackle the cost-of-living crisis and create the new jobs that are essential to it, unless we break this pattern.</p></blockquote><p><br /><b>• He said all parties were to blame for the &quot;century-long centralisation of England&quot;.</b></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Governments of both parties have not done nearly enough to give the tools to the brilliant people, talented individuals, dynamic businesses of our great towns and cities to do the job they want to do.</p></blockquote><p><b>• He praised <a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/no-stone-unturned-in-pursuit-of-growth\">the report that Lord Heseltine compiled for the government, No Stone Unturned, proposing economic decentralisation to the regions.</a></b></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Lord Heseltine’s review called for massive funding to be devolved to Britain’s cities. </p><p>And they flunked the test.<br /></p><p>Cities like Birmingham put in the work to prepare for it.<br /></p><p>But David Cameron and George Osborne allocated just &pound;2bn for a Local Growth Fund in their Spending Review.<br /></p><p> Just a fifth of what Michael Heseltine asked for.</p><p>The best report this government has produced has been the one that they have most ignored.<br /></p><p>We can and must do a lot better than that.</p></blockquote><p><b>• Miliband said Labour would devolve new powers to city-regions. </b>This is how the party explained it in a briefing note.</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Ed Miliband and Ed Balls are today writing to all local authorities, universities and LEPs [local enterprise partnership] setting out this road map and inviting them to prepare plans meeting the conditions which could be brought forward early in the next Parliament. </p><p> Authorities which bring forward plans in the first nine months of the next Parliament will in return receive a devolution deal finalised in the first spending review period of a Labour Government.</p><p> In the next stage of his review, Lord Adonis will build on the approach set out by Lord Heseltine’s Review. The Heseltine Review set out an “indicative list of central budgets” which could be considered for devolution over four years. But the Government allocated just &pound;2bn for a Local Growth Fund in their Spending Review for 2015-16. Lord Adonis has been asked by Ed Miliband to go further and examine every line of the spending set out by Lord Heseltine so that significantly more funding can be devolved.</p></blockquote><p>And this is how Labour explained what councils and LEPs would have to do to get money from central government.</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>1. Putting in place stronger political governance to drive economic leadership and decision-taking at city-region and county-region level.</p><p>2. Properly integrating a single Local Enterprise Partnership working closely with, but entirely independent of, the combined authority so that businesses are fully engaged in decision making and signed up to the local blueprint.</p><p>3. Developing an economic strategy, clearly focused on the creation of well paid jobs and reducing any productivity gap between the city region and top performing regions of the UK.</p></blockquote><p><b>• Miliband accused the government of not creating enough good jobs.</b></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>In the last few years, we’ve seen employment in low paid sectors rise twice as fast as in higher paid sectors. </p><p>George Osborne thinks that creating more and more insecure, low paid, low skilled jobs is good enough as an answer to our country’s cost-of-living crisis.</p><p>It isn’t.<br /></p><p>That is why he’s part of the problem.<br /></p><p>Not the solution.<br /></p></blockquote><p>This contrasts with <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/2014/apr/07/maria-millers-expenses-controversy-latest-developments-politics-live-blog#block-5342b033e4b03e953afa2e6f\">what Iain Duncan Smith said yesterday, when he defended the idea of getting the unemployed into minimum wage jobs.</a></p><p><b>• Miliband said that George Osborne should have acknowledged the importance of full employment long before now.</b></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Now, I welcome the chancellor’s apparent conversion to the cause of full employment.</p><p>It is 70 years after a British government first dedicated itself to it.</p><p>I guess better late than never.</p></blockquote><p><b>• Miliband said that the Tories were wrong if they thought the living standards crisis was close to being over.</b><br /></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Because they tell us that very soon, on one measure, average wage rises will overtake the level of inflation.</p><p> I hope that happens as soon as possible.</p><p>And any progress in people’s living standards is a good thing.<br /></p><p>But it is time the Conservative Party got in touch with reality.<br /></p><p>And here’s a way to do it.<br /></p><p>I suggest to Conservative candidates and the Prime Minister that they go on the doorstep of families in Britain and tell them:<br /></p><p>“Hello I am from the Conservative party.”<br /></p><p>“And I am here to tell you the average of wages has overtaken the CPI measure of inflation and so I can tell you that your cost-of-living crisis is over.”<br /></p></blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343d2cbe4b053db358db080\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T11:45:25.819+01:00\">11.45am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Ed Miliband has been taking questions about the Maria Miller affair at his speech in Birmingham. He is not calling for her to resign.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/RebeccaKeating/statuses/453475892002836480\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>. <a href=\"https://twitter.com/Ed_Miliband\">@Ed_Miliband</a>: David Cameron has 'some serious questions to answer' over Maria Miller's approach to expenses probe and'perfunctory' apology</p>— Rebecca Keating (@RebeccaKeating) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/RebeccaKeating/statuses/453475892002836480\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/MichaelPDeacon/statuses/453476202985316352\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Ed Miliband, asked whether Maria Miller should resign: &quot;I'm not calling for that today.&quot; Tomorrow? Thursday? Easter Monday?</p>— Michael Deacon (@MichaelPDeacon) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/MichaelPDeacon/statuses/453476202985316352\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/iainjwatson/statuses/453477278358720512\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Ed Miliband says right to reform MPs expenses but miller case raise issues about how decisions are made 'but not in a knee jerk way'</p>— iain watson (@iainjwatson) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/iainjwatson/statuses/453477278358720512\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/JasonGroves1/statuses/453479576115896321\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Ed Miliband not calling for Maria Miller to resign - Labour's had too many expenses problems of its own</p>— Jason Groves (@JasonGroves1) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/JasonGroves1/statuses/453479576115896321\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>I've just finished reading his speech. I will summarise it in a lengthy post shortly.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343cca0e4b06c7e09a601a7\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T11:20:24.552+01:00\">11.20am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>We're going to get an urgent question on parliamentary standards at 12.30pm.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/rosschawkins/statuses/453474926033637376\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Urgent question on Parliamentary Standards 1230 in Commons</p>— Ross Hawkins (@rosschawkins) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/rosschawkins/statuses/453474926033637376\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>Andrew Lansley, the leader of the Commons, is responding.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343c952e4b053db358db072\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T11:04:07.559+01:00\">11.04am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Guido Fawkes has posted on Twitter more details of the Survation poll I mentioned earlier. (See <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/2014/apr/08/maria-millers-expenses-controversy-latest-developments-politics-live-blog#block-5343b9ece4b053db358db056\">10.02am.)</a></p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/GuidoFawkes/statuses/453466877084200960\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>55% say Miller is the worst expenses cheat since 2009 <a href=\"http://t.co/Y1qkZ2OllS\">http://t.co/Y1qkZ2OllS</a> <a href=\"http://t.co/4oSbEgnak9\">pic.twitter.com/4oSbEgnak9</a></p>— Guido Fawkes (@GuidoFawkes) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/GuidoFawkes/statuses/453466877084200960\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343c531e4b06c7e09a6019a\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T10:49:51.628+01:00\">10.49am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><b>Alastair Campbell</b> is the man credited with saying that a political crisis cannot go on for nine days <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/2014/apr/07/maria-millers-expenses-controversy-latest-developments-politics-live-blog#block-534254cbe4b03e953afa2dda\">(or 13, or 11, or seven - no one is quite sure) </a>without someone having to resign.</p><p>At the BBC they're counting. This morning's radio news reports made the point that this was Miller's sixth day in the headlines. (They're starting from Thursday last week.)</p><p>Campbell himself thinks that Miller has stayed too long already.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/campbellclaret/statuses/453419020134658048\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Whatever my rule was, Maria Miller is breaking it.Trouble is Dave likes to have fights not worth having so he can avoid the ones that matter</p>— Alastair Campbell (@campbellclaret) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/campbellclaret/statuses/453419020134658048\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343c325e4b06c7e09a60197\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T10:40:13.018+01:00\">10.40am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Sometimes tabloid papers coin a nickname that brilliantly encapsulates a figure they either love or loathe.</p><p>And sometimes they don't quite pull it off. The Sun's decision to christen Maria Miller &quot;the Millerpede&quot; probably comes into the category.</p><p>Still, that hasn't discouraged them. They are unveiling a banner about her outside the Commons.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/peterdominiczak/statuses/453464060127113216\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>There is currently a Sun newspaper &quot;Millerpede&quot; banner being photographed outside Parliament.</p>— Peter Dominiczak (@peterdominiczak) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/peterdominiczak/statuses/453464060127113216\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/tnewtondunn/statuses/453464846911414272\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>All will be revealed soon; MT <a href=\"https://twitter.com/christopherhope\">@christopherhope</a> It looks like The Sun is photographing a &quot;Miller-pede&quot; banner <a href=\"http://t.co/2who4l9eTA\">pic.twitter.com/2who4l9eTA</a></p>— Tom Newton Dunn (@tnewtondunn) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/tnewtondunn/statuses/453464846911414272\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343b457e4b053db358db04b\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T10:32:55.617+01:00\">10.32am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">What the papers are saying about Maria Miller</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>You can read all today’s Guardian politics stories <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/all\">here. </a>And all the politics stories filed yesterday, including some in today’s paper, are <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/apr/07/all\">here.</a></p><p>As for the rest of the papers, here’s <a href=\"http://www.politicshome.com/uk/todays_must_reads.html\">the PoliticsHome list of top 10 must-reads</a>, here’s <a href=\"http://www.conservativehome.com/frontpage/2014/04/newslinks-for-tuesday-8th-april-2014.html\">the ConservativeHome round-up of the politics stories in today’s papers</a> and here’s <a href=\"http://www.newstatesman.com/staggers/2014/04/morning-call-pick-papers-1\">the New Statesman’s list of top 10 comment articles.</a></p><p>And here is a round-up of the most interesting Maria Miller coverage.</p><h2>News stories</h2><p><a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/10751255/Tory-MPs-call-for-Miller-to-be-sacked.html\">• The Daily Telegraph says Graham Brady, chairman of the 1922 committee of Conservative backbenchers, met David Cameron last night to tell him Tory MPs want Miller to go.</a></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Graham Brady, the chairman of the 1922 Committee of backbench MPs, met the Prime Minister on Monday to tell him that MPs from across the party were calling for Mrs Miller to go ...</p><p> A source said senior members of the 1922 Committee were “in no doubt that this is absolutely toxic” for the party. Mr Brady would “make that very clear” to Mr Cameron ...</p><p>Some backbenchers have set a deadline of Wednesday for Mrs Miller to go. They are threatening to confront Mr Cameron if she is still in place when he addresses the committee before the Commons starts its Easter recess ...</p><p>One member of the 1922 Committee Executive said: “She should do the honourable thing and resign. She has been foolish and selfish. She is damaging the party and putting the Prime Minister in a very difficult position.</p></blockquote><p><a href=\"http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/politics/article4057207.ece\">• Francis Elliott in the Times (paywall) says a former colleague of Miller's has disputed a key element of the argument she used to justify her expenses claim.</a></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p> A former colleague of Mrs Miller’s has also disputed a key justification for her expense claim — also challenged by the independent watchdog — that her main home was in her Hampshire constituency, allowing her to claim mortgage costs on her London house. </p><p> Mrs Miller claimed parliamentary allowances for her Victorian terrace property in Wimbledon on the basis that it was her “second home”. In her evidence to the watchdog, she repeatedly insisted that she spent more nights in her constituency residence than in her larger home in Wimbledon. </p><p> However, Phil Heath, a former Conservative councillor and deputy mayor who worked on the MP’s election campaign, told BBC South: “She would come back once every couple of weeks on a Friday to do a surgery then she’d be sheepishly back up to London — her family were there, her children were there. Her house in Basingstoke, whenever we had a meeting there, there was no family there. So that was definitely her second home.” </p><p> A Tory Party spokesman questioned Mr Heath’s impartiality, saying: “Phil Heath was expelled from the Conservative Party for aggressive behaviour. He now works as part of the Ukip campaign, so clearly has an agenda.” </p></blockquote><p>The Daily Mail also uses this allegation from Heath as the thrust of its main Miller story.<br /></p><p><a href=\"http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/maria-miller-expenses-row-embattled-minister-loses-support-amongst-her-own-party-9244781.html\">• Nigel Morris in the Independent says Miller is losing the support of Conservative MPs.</a></p><p><a href=\"http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/news/politics/5556611/tory-MPs-maria-millers-head-cameron-showdown.html\">• Steve Hawkes in the Sun (paywall) says Tory MPs intend to demand Miller's resignation when Cameron addresses the 1922 committee tomorrow.</a></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>One [backbencher] said: &quot;He's looking after his own and it's going to cost us vote. Whatever happens now we have lost credibility.&quot;</p></blockquote><h2>Editorials</h2><p>And here is what papers are saying in their editorials</p><p><a href=\"http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/leaders/article4057006.ece\">• The Times (paywall) says Miller should resign.</a></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Maria Miller should resign. If she does not appreciate the need, the Prime Minister should make it clear to her. It seems at the moment as if she and those who work in Downing Street are almost the only people in the country who do not recognise that it is time for her to go. In both cases, obstinacy is getting in the way of good judgment.</p></blockquote><p><a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/debate/article-2599357/DAILY-MAIL-COMMENT-Now-make-union-fit-members.html\">• The Daily Mail says Cameron has seriously misjudged the public mood.</a></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>As for David Cameron, at last he seems to acknowledge that there may be a case for toughening up Parliament’s regulatory regime. But still he stands by Mrs Miller.</p><p>The longer this affair drags on, the more toxic it becomes for the Tories. This paper cannot see the story dying of its own accord.</p></blockquote><p>• The Sun says Miller should have been sacked days ago.<br /></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>David Cameron' s misplaced loyalty to Maria Miller is costing him votes with ever hour that ticks by.</p></blockquote><p>• The Daily Mirror says Cameron is &quot;treating the British public with contempt by protecting Tory expenses fiddler Maria Miller&quot;.</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>People won't fall for it, Dave. They think Miller should go. The longer you defend the indefensible the more out of touch you become.</p></blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343befce4b053db358db05d\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T10:19:23.802+01:00\">10.19am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><b>Zac Goldsmith </b>has told Radio 5 Live this morning he's &quot;surprised&quot; Maria Miller hasn't already resigned.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/vicderbyshire/statuses/453449874617688064\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>10am: Conservative MP <a href=\"https://twitter.com/ZacGoldsmith\">@ZacGoldsmith</a> tells me he's &quot;surprised&quot; <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23MariaMiller&amp;src=hash\">#MariaMiller</a> hasn't resigned ..full interview after 10 on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/bbc5live\">@bbc5live</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23expenses&amp;src=hash\">#expenses</a></p>— Victoria Derbyshire (@vicderbyshire) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/vicderbyshire/statuses/453449874617688064\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343b9ece4b053db358db056\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T10:02:50.778+01:00\">10.02am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>And here's another Maria Miller poll. <a href=\"http://www.breitbart.com/Breitbart-London/2014/04/08/poll-shows-voters-at-odds-with-conservatives-over-miller\">A Survation survey for Breitbart London (a rightwing, libertarian website) and Conservative Grassroots says that 34% of those who voted Conservative in 2010 say they would reconsider how they vote on the basis of Miller's conduct and David Cameron's response to it.</a></p><p>(Polls like this need to be treated with even more caution than normal ones. It's based on a leading question, because you are unlikely to want to admit that the conduct of a minister is something that you will just ignore, and in practice single controversies of this kind, on their own, tend not to have much impact on voting intention.)</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343b608e4b053db358db050\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T09:46:51.465+01:00\">9.46am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><b>Zac Goldsmith</b>, the Conservative MP, has written <a href=\"http://www.conservativehome.com/platform/2014/04/from-zacgoldsmith-the-maria-miller-controversy-is-a-reminder-of-why-we-need-a-proper-right-of-recall.html\">a piece for ConservativeHome saying the Maria Miller affair underlines the need for a proper &quot;recall&quot; law giving the voters the opportunity to force an MP to stand again in a byelection if they are unhappy with his or her conduct.</a></p><p>The government is promising to legislate for recall in the final session of parliament. But, as Goldsmith points out, under Nick Clegg's plan (he's in charge of this legislation), the committee that would decide whether or not to allow a recall would be the same one, the standards committee, that watered down the report saying Miller should pay back &pound;45,000.</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>When it comes to the technicalities of financial wrongdoing, it probably makes sense for a specialised independent body to lay out the facts, and make recommendations.</p><p>But what seems to have slipped the net in recent debates is the fact that we already have an independent body, capable and uniquely qualified to pass judgment on MPs. It’s called the electorate. The only difficulty, for now, is that they don’t have the powers to do so.</p><p>I have no idea what sort of constituency MP Maria Miller is, but I am certain that, in a mature and functioning democracy, her constituents should be able to hold her to account at all times, and not just at the election. If events cause a majority of constituents to lose confidence in their MP, they should have the right to remove that MP. It is a right that shouldn’t be limited to issues of expenses. It should simply be a matter of confidence.</p></blockquote> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-710d199a-6331-4583-8925-d7d9aadaa2be\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/4/8/1396946804717/4d174ba1-fa48-47ad-abf4-209ef4e3c6f6-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Zac Goldsmith\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Zac Goldsmith Photograph: See Li/Demotix/Corbis</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343b27be4b06c7e09a60170\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T09:25:53.242+01:00\">9.25am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><a href=\"http://www.itv.com/news/update/2014-04-08/poll-69-of-tory-supporters-think-miller-shouldve-gone/\">According to a ComRes poll of Conservative supporters, 69% of them think Maria Miller should resign.</a></p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343ac5de4b053db358db035\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T09:03:51.722+01:00\">9.03am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>I'm told there's no need to get excited about the idea of Maria Miller going into Number 10 early today. She was there for a political cabinet meeting starting at 8.30am. The full cabinet starts at 9.30am. A Number 10 source says that the suggestion that Miller was turning up early for a special meeting with Cameron was &quot;total nonsense&quot; and that she still has Cameron's &quot;strong backing&quot;.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5343a4f4e4b06c7e09a60155\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-04-08T08:41:12.264+01:00\">8.41am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>It's another tricky day for Maria Miller. Today the Daily Telegraph and the Times - the two leading Tory &quot;broadsheets&quot; - are leading on stories saying Conservative MPs want her to be sacked.</p><p>And here are this morning's developments.</p><p><b>• Miller has gone into Downing Street without speaking to reporters. </b></p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/SophyRidgeSky/statuses/453430450535792640\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Maria Miller has just done possibly the quickest EVER entry into No10. Drove up in car, back to cameras, no response to shouted questions</p>— Sophy Ridge (@SophyRidgeSky) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/SophyRidgeSky/statuses/453430450535792640\">April 8, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>There's a cabinet meeting this morning at 9am, but minister's don't normally arrive 40 minutes early. Perhaps David Cameron wants a word ....</p><p><b>• Boris Johnson, the Conservative mayor of London, has offered only lukewarm support for Miller on the Today programme. </b>He sidestepped questions about whether she should stay, but eventually said he felt sympathetic towards her.</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>She is staying. I don't know the facts of the case in great detail but it seems to me she is being hounded quite a lot and I suppose my natural sympathies go out to people being in a hounded situation. How about that? </p></blockquote><p>Johnson also said he supported a fully independent system for investigating complaints against MPs.</p><p><b>• David Laws, the Lib Dem schools minister, has also called for a review of the way MPs police their own conduct. </b>Speaking about Miller, he said:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>She's another member of the government and of course she has my support, just as she has the prime minister's, which is the support that really counts. I'm just junior minister. It's the view of the prime minister and the view of the standards committee that really counts.</p></blockquote><p>I'll be following all the latest developments in the saga as the day goes on.</p><p>And here's the full agenda for the day.</p><p><i>10am:</i> The Commons Treasury committee takes evidence form the insurance industry and tax experts on the budget.</p><p><i>10.30am:</i><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/apr/07/ed-miliband-labour-city-regions-uk-growth\"> Ed Miliband gives a speech in Birmingham saying Labour would put powerful &quot;city-region&quot; government at the heart of a Labour attempt to rebalance growth in the UK.</a></p><p><i>11.30am:</i> Michael Dugher, the shadow Cabinet Office minister, gives a speech on jobs and growth.</p><p><i>2.45pm:</i> Theresa May, the home secretary, gives evidence to the Commons home affairs committee.</p><p>As usual, I will also be flagging up any breaking political news, posting summaries with a round-up of all the day’s developments, and highlighting the most interesting political articles on the web.<br /></p><p>If you want to follow me on Twitter, I’m on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/AndrewSparrow\">@AndrewSparrow.</a></p> </div> </div><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/433981948|2014-05-04T10:23:41Z|079af571ca39b1a4babae41b3963c826c8339114 -->",
